1
00:00:40,707 --> 00:00:44,939
Astronaut Forrest...
you give us hope.

2
00:00:45,045 --> 00:00:47,036
And your great accomplishment...

3
00:00:47,113 --> 00:00:49,775
will be edged
in the history of mankind.

4
00:00:54,320 --> 00:00:56,379
You're not alone.

5
00:00:56,456 --> 00:01:02,417
People from all over the world
are keeping their eyes on you.

6
00:01:02,495 --> 00:01:06,124
So please, don't lose
your hope and faith.

7
00:01:08,568 --> 00:01:10,399
We'll be praying for you...

8
00:01:10,470 --> 00:01:12,768
and your safe journey home.

9
00:01:47,607 --> 00:01:52,135
What is it that inspires
mankind to take great risk?

10
00:01:54,481 --> 00:01:56,676
Why is it that throughout
history...

11
00:01:56,783 --> 00:02:01,311
humans have been driven
to explore distant uncharted
places...

12
00:02:01,387 --> 00:02:04,584
despite the possibility
of no return?

13
00:02:08,161 --> 00:02:13,189
In the case of Europa, the icy,
mysterious moon of Jupiter...

14
00:02:13,299 --> 00:02:16,826
that inspiration came
in the form of photographs.

15
00:02:18,505 --> 00:02:21,201
Photographs that revealed life.

16
00:02:25,145 --> 00:02:29,548
These ghostly images gave the
entire human race unrepentant
knowledge...

17
00:02:29,649 --> 00:02:33,551
that life as we know it
is not an isolated event...

18
00:02:33,653 --> 00:02:38,454
reserved merely for Earth.

19
00:02:38,525 --> 00:02:42,552
But rather a miracle that
is pervasive throughout
the cosmos.

20
00:02:45,865 --> 00:02:50,700
And for the first time
since the 1970's...

21
00:02:50,770 --> 00:02:55,901
humankind, once again, sought
to set foot on a distant world.

22
00:03:00,413 --> 00:03:02,142
Hey, kids.

23
00:03:02,215 --> 00:03:06,743
Um, I want to know, how do you
go to the bathroom in space?

24
00:03:06,853 --> 00:03:09,879
I'll answer this one. Check
this out. We have a small--

25
00:03:09,956 --> 00:03:13,187
Actually, there is a little bit
of gravity on the ship...

26
00:03:13,259 --> 00:03:16,592
so, so going to the bathroom...

27
00:03:16,696 --> 00:03:19,324
in space is a lot like going
to the bathroom on Earth.

28
00:03:19,399 --> 00:03:23,893
Well, I think the kids would
enjoy how number one works.

29
00:03:23,970 --> 00:03:25,164
Next question.

30
00:03:29,242 --> 00:03:33,178

In the days after NASA retired
the space shuttle program...

31
00:03:33,246 --> 00:03:36,841
and since the abandonment
of the International Space
Station...

32
00:03:36,916 --> 00:03:39,350
the world has had to turn
to private enterprise...

33
00:03:39,419 --> 00:03:42,616
when it comes to getting man
back into space.

34
00:03:42,722 --> 00:03:45,691
The most influential name in
space exploration has been...

35
00:03:45,758 --> 00:03:48,283
without a doubt,
Walter Moffitt.

36
00:03:49,596 --> 00:03:51,086
Whales on Europa.

37
00:03:51,164 --> 00:03:53,792
Yes... every time I see these
latest pictures...

38
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:55,925
man, it gives chills
down my spine.

39
00:03:56,002 --> 00:03:58,470
Which brings me to my next
question... of pictures.

40
00:03:58,571 --> 00:04:00,300
Mm-hm.

41
00:04:00,406 --> 00:04:03,068
We have dozens
and dozens of pictures.
Lots of pictures.

42
00:04:03,142 --> 00:04:08,307
NASA is preparing a submersible
rover to dive under the ice.

43
00:04:10,250 --> 00:04:12,047
NASA and its rover...

44
00:04:12,118 --> 00:04:14,245
My name is Gavin Hayden.

45
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:17,619
Why aren't you wearing
any spacesuits?

46
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:20,250
The space suits, or EVAs...

47
00:04:20,326 --> 00:04:22,658
are used for extra-vehicular
activities...

48
00:04:22,762 --> 00:04:25,754
so, that would be outside
the ship.

49
00:04:25,832 --> 00:04:28,824
But I suppose they could be
used in an emergency.

50
00:04:28,935 --> 00:04:31,495
About two hours worth
of life support.

51
00:04:33,172 --> 00:04:37,404
Charlie, it takes NASA
a year just to pass gas.

52
00:04:37,477 --> 00:04:39,775
They have quadruple redundancy
in everything they do...

53
00:04:39,846 --> 00:04:42,644
in their engineering chain,
and you name it.

54
00:04:42,715 --> 00:04:45,275
I have respect for NASA,
but by the time their rover...

55
00:04:45,351 --> 00:04:47,819
gets there, our boys
will be on their way home.

56
00:04:47,887 --> 00:04:51,983
 To accomplish
the 13-year mission to explore
the distant world...

57
00:04:52,058 --> 00:04:57,860
astronauts Nathan Miller and
Michael Forrest are placed into
a deep sleep for six years...

58
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:00,865
as their space craft races
from planet to planet...

59
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:03,629
before speeding off to Europa.

60
00:05:03,703 --> 00:05:08,163
There they will spend one year
in a state-of-the-art
facility...

61
00:05:08,241 --> 00:05:12,268
studying the newly discovered
species of alien giants...

62
00:05:12,345 --> 00:05:14,973
before finally returning home.

63
00:05:15,048 --> 00:05:19,849
My name's Emily. Um, aren't
you going to Venus, 'cause
that's the wrong way?

64
00:05:19,919 --> 00:05:24,117
That is actually
a very astute question.

65
00:05:24,190 --> 00:05:27,489
Um, it has to do with the
orbital ellipses of the
planets...

66
00:05:27,560 --> 00:05:31,360
and a very concerted effort
on the part of the scientists,
as well as ourselves...

67
00:05:31,431 --> 00:05:35,993
to increase the speed of the
ship using not only the earth's
gravitational pull...

68
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:37,536
but Venus as well.

69
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:39,400
Yeah, so what I think my
colleague is trying to say...

70
00:05:39,505 --> 00:05:41,496
it's all about going fast.

71
00:05:41,574 --> 00:05:44,805
So what we're gonna do is spin
around Venus to pick up speed...

72
00:05:44,877 --> 00:05:47,141
then slingshot
from Venus to Earth.

73
00:05:47,213 --> 00:05:50,011
As we get even more speedage,
we're off to Jupiter.

74
00:05:50,083 --> 00:05:53,246
Faster than ever.
Sounds cool, huh?

75
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:58,586
Isn't the redundancy exactly
what is needed here for safety?

76
00:05:58,691 --> 00:06:02,923
There are those who criticize
you who say that you rushed
this mission.

77
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:05,156
This is not meant to be
a disclaimer...

78
00:06:05,231 --> 00:06:10,498
but everybody knows how I feel,
you know, that I'm very
protective of my men.

79
00:06:10,570 --> 00:06:13,198
Columbus went around the world.
Magellan sailed around the whole
planet.

80
00:06:13,272 --> 00:06:16,673
We got guys going to the moon.
They rushed them to the moon.

81
00:06:16,743 --> 00:06:18,108
And that was for a reason.

82
00:06:18,211 --> 00:06:19,940
We need somebody there.

83
00:06:20,046 --> 00:06:23,743
We need somebody to put their
foot in the dust of the moon.

84
00:06:23,816 --> 00:06:26,182
Like many brave explorers
before them...

85
00:06:26,252 --> 00:06:28,413
the two-men crew of Life One...

86
00:06:28,488 --> 00:06:32,584
entrust their lives to their
tiny vessel and to each
other...

87
00:06:32,658 --> 00:06:36,424
for a chance to witness
the extraordinary.

88
00:06:36,496 --> 00:06:42,025
It has been called the most
dangerous whale watching
expedition in history.

89
00:06:42,101 --> 00:06:43,466
When you see the planet...

90
00:06:43,569 --> 00:06:47,300
what does it look like
outside the window?

91
00:06:49,142 --> 00:06:51,372
It looks like stars.

92
00:06:51,444 --> 00:06:55,312
We have heard that this mission
has cost you personally...

93
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:56,780
50 billion dollars.

94
00:06:56,849 --> 00:06:58,146
It cost me a lot.

95
00:06:58,251 --> 00:07:00,787
But look, that's what
we're here for.

96
00:07:00,787 --> 00:07:02,652
That's what we're working,
that's the whole deal.

97
00:07:02,755 --> 00:07:04,882
Think about this for a minute.

98
00:07:04,957 --> 00:07:08,586
These boys are travelling
at the speed of a .45 bullet.

99
00:07:08,661 --> 00:07:10,754
They're sound asleep.

100
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:15,597
They're gonna go around Venus,
past Earth, and then start
orbiting Jupiter.

101
00:07:15,668 --> 00:07:17,602
What a miracle.

102
00:07:17,670 --> 00:07:20,503
They'll see the whales
of Europa.

103
00:07:20,606 --> 00:07:22,972
But they'll be seeing it
with their eyes.

104
00:07:23,042 --> 00:07:25,636
It won't be photographs
from NASA.

105
00:07:25,711 --> 00:07:30,512
Your a man who's wealthy enough
to do anything he wants to do.

106
00:07:30,616 --> 00:07:35,576
Why aren't you up there
with those men right now?

107
00:07:35,655 --> 00:07:40,354
Charlie, I've done everything
I've wanted to do... just about.

108
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:42,951
I'm a bit long in the tooth.

109
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:45,691
I would'a, could'a, should'a...

110
00:07:45,798 --> 00:07:48,961
but it really isn't about me.

111
00:07:49,035 --> 00:07:51,526
It's about future generations.

112
00:07:51,637 --> 00:07:53,867
Can I ask a question?

113
00:07:53,973 --> 00:07:56,703
How is it that you plan
to spend your free time?

114
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:59,175
Space pong.
We actually won't have
a lot of free time.

115
00:07:59,245 --> 00:08:00,803
Now ping pong in space--

116
00:08:00,880 --> 00:08:02,814
We're gonna be doing
experiments 24/7.

117
00:08:02,882 --> 00:08:04,873
Not to mention
a lifetime of study.

118
00:08:04,984 --> 00:08:07,782
Having to cram that
into just one year, so--

119
00:08:07,854 --> 00:08:11,483
Yeah, but in our free time,
I will be in my space suit...

120
00:08:11,557 --> 00:08:15,391
sitting on my porch, reading
from my pocket Shakespeare...

121
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:19,329
by the light of Jupiter
on the horizon.

122
00:08:19,398 --> 00:08:21,992
Um, that sounds beautiful.
Thank you.

123
00:08:22,068 --> 00:08:25,299
Well, I guess it's time
for us to go.

124
00:08:25,371 --> 00:08:28,568
We have a lot of work to do
before we go to sleep.

125
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:31,666
Thank you for your
wonderful question.

126
00:08:31,744 --> 00:08:33,974
Bye-bye.

127
00:08:34,046 --> 00:08:37,015
Thank you, kids.
We'll see you guys in six years.

128
00:11:40,433 --> 00:11:44,199
Nathan!

129
00:11:45,571 --> 00:11:47,596
OMS thrusters check?

130
00:11:47,707 --> 00:11:51,234
OMS thrusters... check.

131
00:11:51,310 --> 00:11:54,211
Hey, pal, how we doing?

132
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:56,111
I am doing just fine.

133
00:12:55,641 --> 00:12:57,131
This is Life One
to Mission Control.

134
00:12:57,209 --> 00:12:59,837
There is a leak in the main
habitation chamber.

135
00:12:59,945 --> 00:13:01,742
I sealed the capsule
and I'm suiting up.

136
00:13:01,814 --> 00:13:04,908
I'll be out of communications
for-- until further notice.

137
00:13:09,121 --> 00:13:10,748
Nathan Miller is dead.

138
00:13:12,825 --> 00:13:14,656
Life One out.

139
00:13:37,683 --> 00:13:39,674
Life One,
this is Mission Control.

140
00:13:39,752 --> 00:13:41,310
We received
your emergency beacon.

141
00:13:41,387 --> 00:13:44,982
We're analyzing all of the data
pouring in right now.

142
00:13:45,057 --> 00:13:48,185
As soon as we have some answers
for you, we'll get back to you.

143
00:13:48,260 --> 00:13:52,560
Acknowledge receipt of this
message. Mission Control out.

144
00:15:33,365 --> 00:15:37,665
Life One, this is Mission
Control. We have multiple
failures of the hull...

145
00:15:37,770 --> 00:15:41,297
in both the capsule
and the habitation module.
We recommend suiting up--

146
00:15:41,373 --> 00:15:42,897
This is Life One to Mission
Control.

147
00:15:42,975 --> 00:15:45,068
There is a leak in the main
habitation chamber.

148
00:15:45,144 --> 00:15:47,612
I've sealed the capsule
and am suiting up.

149
00:15:47,680 --> 00:15:51,582
I'll be out of communications
for 12 hours.
That's great, you're on it.

150
00:15:51,650 --> 00:15:54,118
We'll keep sending more
information as it comes in.

151
00:15:54,186 --> 00:15:56,677
Mission Control out.

Life One out.

152
00:15:58,290 --> 00:16:02,522
This is Life One.

153
00:16:02,628 --> 00:16:05,153
The main habitation
chamber is secure.

154
00:16:08,334 --> 00:16:13,431
The hibernation
and reentry capsule... is--

155
00:16:16,241 --> 00:16:20,678
I'm sorry, I don't know
who you are, um...

156
00:16:20,746 --> 00:16:26,651
Can you find me Ben Elliot
or... Bob Jansen?

157
00:16:26,719 --> 00:16:28,277
Would be great.

158
00:16:31,423 --> 00:16:32,515
This is Life One out.

159
00:16:39,031 --> 00:16:40,999

Space travel is inherently
dangerous.

160
00:16:41,066 --> 00:16:44,126
There could always be a problem.

161
00:16:44,203 --> 00:16:47,639
Let's say on the first leg,
heading towards Venus...

162
00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:51,335
or on the second leg, going
from Venus back to Earth...

163
00:16:51,410 --> 00:16:53,742
aborting the mission
would be relatively simple.

164
00:16:53,846 --> 00:16:56,576
We'd just come home.

165
00:16:56,682 --> 00:17:02,552
We'd actually be asleep at the
time, so we probably wouldn't
know that there was a problem.

166
00:17:02,621 --> 00:17:07,558
Of course, after we make that
last push around Earth and head
towards Jupiter...

167
00:17:07,626 --> 00:17:09,719
well, there's really
no going back.

168
00:17:13,432 --> 00:17:16,162
Life One,
this is Mission Control.

169
00:17:16,235 --> 00:17:20,899
We have Robert Jansen
to come in and talk to you
face-to-face.

170
00:17:20,973 --> 00:17:24,932

All right, great, thanks.

171
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:26,841
Michael?
It's Life One.

172
00:17:26,912 --> 00:17:29,039
No, it's Michael,
and you're Adam and I'm Bob...

173
00:17:29,114 --> 00:17:30,547
so let's cut the jargon.

174
00:17:30,616 --> 00:17:34,017
Michael, hi, it looks like
the space craft...

175
00:17:34,086 --> 00:17:38,853
was more than likely hit
by a micro-meteorite.

176
00:17:38,924 --> 00:17:42,519
Information is coming in and
we're doing our best to process
it as quickly as possible.

177
00:17:42,594 --> 00:17:44,755
Just know that I am here...

178
00:17:44,830 --> 00:17:48,960
and as I know anything,
I will transmit back to you.

179
00:17:49,068 --> 00:17:50,433
Bob out.

180
00:17:55,674 --> 00:17:57,369
This is Life One.

181
00:17:59,478 --> 00:18:01,036
It's good to see you, Bob.

182
00:18:02,948 --> 00:18:04,381
Damage report.

183
00:18:04,450 --> 00:18:06,577
Life support is solid.

184
00:18:06,652 --> 00:18:08,984
And oxygen is holding,
for now.

185
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:12,888
The habitation module
is stabilized and we're at 1.0
of earth gravity.

186
00:18:12,958 --> 00:18:18,794
So whatever hit us, must have
not been big enough to knock
us off our spin.

187
00:18:18,864 --> 00:18:22,664
The central fuel tank
and booster engine are
in the numbers.

188
00:18:22,768 --> 00:18:24,736
Nuclear reactor remains
unbreached...

189
00:18:24,803 --> 00:18:28,000
and all radiation shielding
is functioning well.

190
00:18:28,107 --> 00:18:32,976
Europa habitation ballast array
and all contents including ice
drill platform.

191
00:18:33,045 --> 00:18:38,278
Inflatable habitat
and mini submersible
are reading 1 00 percent.

192
00:18:42,321 --> 00:18:44,084
Looks like the only thing
that we lost, actually...

193
00:18:44,156 --> 00:18:46,590
was the hibernation
and reentry capsule.

194
00:18:52,731 --> 00:18:56,132
I'll do another diagnostic check
and I'll be in touch.

195
00:18:56,201 --> 00:18:57,998
Thanks, Bob.

196
00:18:58,070 --> 00:18:59,833
Life One out.

197
00:19:08,814 --> 00:19:10,714
Life One,
this is Mission Control.

198
00:19:10,816 --> 00:19:13,944
We have an update
on the situation...

199
00:19:14,019 --> 00:19:18,183
but Mr. Moffitt would like
to deliver this message himself.

200
00:19:19,391 --> 00:19:20,983
Thank you.

201
00:19:25,264 --> 00:19:28,722
Michael... Walter Moffit.

202
00:19:30,602 --> 00:19:33,298
Listen, first of all...

203
00:19:33,372 --> 00:19:38,173
we deeply regret
the loss of Nathaniel.

204
00:19:38,243 --> 00:19:42,407
And there's not much you can say
about a thing like this...

205
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:46,848
but Mr. Jeffs has taking over
for Mr. Elliot...

206
00:19:46,919 --> 00:19:49,183
who passed away about two years
ago in a heart attack.

207
00:19:51,456 --> 00:19:55,392
A lot's changed since
you've been gone.

208
00:19:55,460 --> 00:20:01,888
And on that note, we've decided
to abort the mission.

209
00:20:01,967 --> 00:20:05,835
I'm looking forward
to talking to you.

210
00:20:05,904 --> 00:20:07,769
Mission out.

211
00:20:36,668 --> 00:20:39,068
Hi, Mike, my name is Irwin
and this is my family...

212
00:20:39,137 --> 00:20:40,900
Mila and Drew.

213
00:20:40,973 --> 00:20:44,374
We'd just like to thank you for
being our eyes in another world.

214
00:20:44,443 --> 00:20:46,638
Bye!
Bye!

215
00:20:46,745 --> 00:20:48,269
Bye.

216
00:20:51,116 --> 00:20:53,710

This is Life One.

217
00:20:53,785 --> 00:20:59,724
I have received your message
and am aborting the mission
to Europa.

218
00:20:59,791 --> 00:21:02,954
Given our current position,
we will continue our present
course...

219
00:21:03,028 --> 00:21:08,557
past Venus as scheduled and
toward Earth as scheduled.

220
00:21:08,634 --> 00:21:11,797
At which point,
we will execute a Leg 3 abort...

221
00:21:11,870 --> 00:21:15,931
scrapping the slingshot maneuver
to Europa... from Earth.

222
00:21:19,544 --> 00:21:22,012
I'll make the changes necessary
for our break in procedure...

223
00:21:22,114 --> 00:21:24,139
and preparation for reentry...

224
00:21:24,216 --> 00:21:26,150
and thereby an end
to the mission.

225
00:21:28,320 --> 00:21:30,151
This is Life One out.

226
00:21:33,292 --> 00:21:35,760
Okay, this is all very exciting.

227
00:21:35,827 --> 00:21:37,920
Hey, ease up, man.
Smile!

228
00:21:37,996 --> 00:21:40,624
It's for the kids.
It's good PR, hit the button.

229
00:21:50,809 --> 00:21:53,334

This is Life One.

230
00:21:53,412 --> 00:21:57,712
It's been 24 hours
since the accident.

231
00:21:57,816 --> 00:22:02,651
My hibernation sickness
is starting to wear off.

232
00:22:06,892 --> 00:22:09,190
The food recycling system
is up and running.

233
00:22:09,261 --> 00:22:11,627
We're at 1 00 percent.

234
00:22:11,697 --> 00:22:16,828
Obviously most of the comforts
of home are locked away
in the Europa.

235
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:20,861
Habitation ballast array.

236
00:22:20,939 --> 00:22:23,407
So I won't get
my comfortable chair.

237
00:22:23,508 --> 00:22:27,672
But I am gonna miss my bed,
and the window for that matter.

238
00:22:30,515 --> 00:22:33,245
We're only supposed to spend
a week to two weeks
in this chamber...

239
